# 7. CONCLUSION WITH SUMMARY 

We conclude by summarizing our findings in Tables 2 to 4. Each table considers one of the three separation properties. The right column describes the property of the completion of a distributive lattice, the left column the corresponding property satisfied by the lattice, and the center column the dual condition on the Priestley space. Within each table, the conditions are arranged from the weakest to the strongest.

For $\mathrm{A} \in$ DLat, recall the following notions from the end of Section 4 relating to subfitness:

- A is $\mathcal{B} \mathcal{L}$-subfit if $\mathcal{B} \mathcal{L} A$ is subfit (equivalently, $p \mathcal{O}(A$ is subfit);
- A is $\mathcal{J}$-subfit ${ }^{10}$ if $\mathcal{M}$ is subfit;

For $\mathrm{A} \in$ DLat, consider the following definitions relating to regularity:

- A is $\mathcal{D} M$-regular if $\mathcal{D} M A$ is regular;
- A is $\mathcal{B} \mathcal{L}$-regular if $\mathcal{B} \mathcal{L} A$ is regular (equivalently, $p \mathcal{O}(A$ is regular);

[^0]
[^0]:    ${ }^{10}$ This should not be confused with the notion of ideally subfit introduced in [DIM21, Def. 2.13] (which is of novel interest only when $A$ is unbounded).

